text: After many long awaited months I finally had the pleasure of watching,"Sorry to Bother You". In the wake of many abysmal films, this film was refreshingly creative, deep, current, metaphorical, and ground breaking. Long after the film has ended it leaves you wondering, "what the hell was that?" A underrated and uncomfortable to watch ---masterpiece. That forces one to see and understand the power of racism, and how it works in our society today. A picture that requires one to self-examine one's own moral standing, and what they are willing to do when confronted with evil. The trailer does it no justice. Go watch it!

Even though i am Mexican-American, i have been speaking like a white non-Hispanic Michigander for so many years.  When i first traveled to Detroit, MI back in August 1983 with both my mother and my younger (half)-brother for two weeks, the only thing that i was able to do was to adhere to the 'social norms' ‚Äì linguistic; sartorial; cultural; etc. ‚Äì of young white non-Hispanic Michiganders residing in both Macomb and Oakland Counties.  The 'sensibilities' of the family matriarch ‚Äì whom my mother has known for several decades ‚Äì have always gravitated toward the Deep South.
